largest-series-product: Do not test digits/slices

The digits and slices functions are internal implementation details and
thus the test case for the largest-series-product problem should not be
concerned with testing them. The series tests could potentially be moved
to the series exercise (already implemented by this track).

Their presence may cause students to falsely think that their solution
has to use these two functions, instead of the alternative
implementation of only iterating through the digits once.

If it is desired to give hints on how to approach this problem (which
was one advantage of having the digits and slices tests), then consider
including a hints file and/or directory in the largest-series-product
directory.

This PR arises from discussion in
https://github.com/exercism/x-common/issues/192

Raw update on Thu, 02 Nov 2017 20:00:02 UTC

Remove the disable_columns concern

In Rails 4.2 attributes is no longer a simple Hash object so this concern
no longer works.  I attempted to rewrite the concern to work with the new
object (ActiveRecord::AttributeSet) but it's got a much smaller api
surface than a Hash, and as such is much less mutable.  This is probably
a good thing from a library api design, but it makes attempting to hide
db columns from the model much harder.

I tried reverting to the old soluiton of filtering the columns from the
db, but although that meant `type` and `new_url` were no longer in the
attributes for an ImportBatch, they were still defined as attribute
methods on the class (it gets them from the base class which still
includes those columns).  Next approach was to try undef-ing the methods
but I couldn't get it to work without blowing other things up.

In the end I decided the pragmatic thing to do is simply remove the
concern.  Yes an ImportBatch shouldn't really have a type or new_url
attribute, but it's fighting against ActiveRecord to make this happen.

some text, turn entries into buttons and remove the manual build ID
input field

version' in an attempt to be more user-friendly.
- Add a ctrl+shift+click inspector modal for download row
- A `build` JSONField has been added to the cave model, it
completely replaces & deprecates the `buildId` and `buildUserVersion`
columns. A migration has been written that converts the old
format to the new format. See #1534 for a future plan to clean up
database schemas
- In general, be more consistent about how we work with builds
throughout the codebase

Also not in short message:
- Fix global game update check (broken by sqlite-based rewrite, it
was just iterating an empty table of caves..)
- Add the `morphing` field to the caves model and use it to mark
whenever we were doing a 'revert/heal/upgrade' operation
- On launch, when `morphing` is set, force a heal and show a
notification saying what happened. Note that the item doesn't open
automatically after, the jury's out on what the best UX is for that.

Various:
- Introduce `formatBuildVersion` helper (should be in format, erm).
Also, that helper is not used by the revert-cave dialog, it has its
own graphical-oriented formatting.
- Pass 'db' to the preboot reactor via an argument instead of importing

Add Cascade Framework 1.5.0 [author]

Files downloaded on jan 8, 2013

Cascade Framework is a frontend framework focused on CSS, like Twitter
Bootstrap or Zurb Foundation.

Cascade Framework 1.x is written in pure CSS. It supports responsive
design and all modern browsers as well as IE6+. For an optimal balance
between footprint and flexibility, it implements a modifier design
pattern inspired by SMACCS and OOCSS.

In an article posted on October 13, 2013, Crunchify lists Cascade
Framework as #5 in its "Top 5 New and Favorite Responsive Frameworks".
The first four are respectively Bootstrap, Cardinal, TypePlate and
Furrato.

In an article posted on October 24, 2013, CodeGeekz lists it among "12
Fresh and Useful Frameworks". Other projects listed are Gumby, Solved by
Flexbox, UI Kit, SkelJS, Cardinal, Layers CSS, Grid Forms, Gridism,
Maxmert, Rocket CSS and Kube Framework.

Linux portal Linuxlinks lists Cascade Framework as one of the ten
"finest open source lightweight frameworks to kick start CSS and HTML
projects". Other projects listed are Quantum Framework, Pure, Baseline,
HTML KickStart, Base, KNACSS, Toast, Motherplate and HTML5 Boilerplate.

Cascade Framework was also Softpedia's Script of the day on September 6,
2013.

At the moment of this commit, Cascade Framework has 97 stars on its main
repo and 39 stars on its mirror repo.

bdw-gc: build static library

Many libraries (e.g. libyaml, libevent) available on Homebrew
contain both the static and dynamic versions of the library.
bdw-gc by default only compiles the dynamic version. This
commit enables building the static libgc.a to allow for
consumers to statically link this library in their applications.

One primary use-case is programs written in Crystal, which uses
bdw-gc for garbage collection by default.
